Was it yesterday?

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:33.200
Yesterday, I think it was.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:34.440
Oh, yes.

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.800
Yeah, yesterday morning I talked to Laura.

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:40.360
But you were talking before that.

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:43.080
Only to arrange a time.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:45.480
Oh, I see.

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:45.960
Yeah.

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:47.480
Because I went to Laura's wedding.

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:50.760
I was 14.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:51.600
Yeah.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:54.080
I was 14 when Laura got married.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.840
I went to her wedding.

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:57.720
Yeah.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:03:59.760
Oh dear.

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:00.600
Yeah.

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:01.040
But it's.

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:03.400
Laura's a good mate, yeah.

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:05.720
But so much has changed, doesn't it, kid?

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:14.360
I mean, in terms of what kids now have compared to what we might remember.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.000
You know, our rule.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.800
The things we could do, the things we were able to do.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:26.880
You know, go out on the beginning of the day if it wasn't a school day.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:29.520
And off you went all day.

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:32.360
Yeah.

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:37.120
I mean, I was talking to Eleanor.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.840
And I was saying, when we went to school, you have to go.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:42.000
You have to go in the snow.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.240
None of them closed.

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:46.680
The schools didn't close like they do now.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:50.960
Anything happened, the schools closed.

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:51.920
That one like that.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.120
We used to come home, oh my god.

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.960
In all kinds of winds and weathers.

00:04:56.960 --> 00:05:00.600
But now today, they closed it.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:03.880
I could have snowed.

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:07.400
We used to go in the sky.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:08.320
They never closed.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:10.400
They closed.

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:13.800
That just meant playtime was more fun.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:16.000
Yeah.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.920
And then you'd come in crying.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:20.760
Soaking wet.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:22.680
Snowballs.

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:25.000
I know you're going to come in crying.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.560
Yeah.

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:29.760
And even if you were the one who threw the first one.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.720
Yes.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:35.280
Did Laura tell us you worked in the colonial center?

00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:36.480
Yeah, yeah, she did.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:37.960
She did.

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:39.280
We were good kids.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:41.640
I said, we never had a lot, but we were happy.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:43.720
My mother always said that.

00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:46.680
And then they used to say, oh, ma'am.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:48.520
So and so and so and so.

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:50.880
They had bikes for Christmas.

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:52.760
And they sat near there.

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:54.360
Mama's slapping hands on the table.

00:05:54.360 --> 00:05:55.760
She said, it's your bike.

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:57.160
Those people are going to eat.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:02.920
She always threw that.

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:05.240
Mind you, oh, god.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.120
We had a good upbringing.

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:09.280
There was five of us.

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:10.600
And then my father went to see it.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:14.160
And then my mother used to take us all to the shelters.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:17.720
In the night, you know, the head-in shelters.

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:20.960
Because you remember the Second World War.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:21.600
You were younger.

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:22.880
Oh, yeah.

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:26.080
I was only 17.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:27.960
I was seven.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.040
When the war started, yeah.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:32.160
What do you remember of it, Cain?

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:33.640
Everything.

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:37.000
The bombing and all things.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.280
You know, we'd be in the shelter.

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:42.040
We knew we were going to eat, you know what I mean?

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.680
In the night.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:48.800
And it was on Butte Road, all the shelters.

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:52.240
And then this, because Mama had five of us.

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:54.120
And I was just little.

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:55.920
And my mother had it on the lap.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.200
The tears was running from my mother's eyes.

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:01.720
Aunt Juarez.

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:03.800
She was a bigot, that one.

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:07.560
I said, oh, Mama, I'll throw this water running on me.

00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:10.480
Mama said she was thinking about, oh, what am I

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.160
going to do with all these bombs?

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:12.880
You know what I mean?

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:16.920
What am I going to do to my kids?

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:18.320
She said that.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:19.720
And that's how I remember then.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:21.920
And the woman next to my mother said,

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:24.400
oh, that's a ticket I'd love.

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:26.960
My mother said, oh, I don't smoke.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:28.240
I said, let's smoke.

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:29.240
Oh, I'll throw it to you.

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:31.000
It'll calm your nerves.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.320
So the next night, my mother said,

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:38.240
oh, I'll buy a packet of cigarettes.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:40.160
I'll take the woman, you know, and I'm back.

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:42.720
You boy didn't want me back.

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:46.360
I'm also sorry my mother's smoking.

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:47.840
I think he hates him.

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:49.320
I think he hates him.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:51.560
People used to think it was good for them.

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:59.200
But then when he was 80, the doctor said,

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.320
keep going through it.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:02.520
I forgot what that doctor was there.

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:05.080
You know, because I've had chest and I've lunged

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:05.960
and I've had.

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:10.840
And he said, oh, Mrs. Freeman, you've got to.

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:14.000
You've got to stop smoking.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:15.800
So she said, oh, yes, I will.

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:18.200
He said, you said that last time.

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:19.440
And anyway, she stopped.

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:22.160
She was 80.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:27.000
And he said, oh, your chest and this and that.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.880
Well, my mother didn't do bad.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:31.600
She didn't pass as a 94.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:33.160
But that was good going, wasn't it?

00:08:33.160 --> 00:08:34.520
Yeah.

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:35.400
Yeah.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:38.040
And she finished smoking when she was 80.

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:42.440
And then my father and me, dad used to go upstairs and smoke.

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:44.120
And I used to go in the kitchen.

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:46.920
And she'd say, look, I'm not spoiling your enjoyment

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:48.760
because I finished.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:49.400
You know what?

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:53.560
After she finished smoking for a while, she said,

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:55.960
after the meal, she said, put it in the ashtray.

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:00.000
Oh, it's a laugh.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.400
You see?

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:07.720
But once the ashtray is happy, it's a habit, she said.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:10.480
Well, it kept going on and on and on for my mother.

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:13.200
Because you could smoke on the buses then.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:17.560
And then we'd have the skinheads go to Langdonk on the bus.

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:19.880
You know, at the back.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:23.280
And we'd have the skinheads going to Langdonk.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.040
And she was 80 then.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:28.240
And we got there and we said, oh.

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:30.480
And that was the last skinhead she had.

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:31.600
That was good going.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:33.280
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:35.560
Just stopped just like that.

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:38.960
Yeah, but strong women.

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:40.440
Strong women.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:41.800
Yeah.

00:09:41.800 --> 00:09:47.040
I mean, my nan always used to say, the men can think,

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.480
but the women run the community.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:50.680
That's it.

00:09:50.680 --> 00:09:55.800
We just let the men pretend, she used to say.

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:57.080
Yeah.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:57.960
Still true.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:09:59.560
Still true.

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:01.520
That's it.

